task_description:
In the  experiment, each participant is given 36 different proposals to respond to. Each is designated by a trial number in the data set This gives 36 instances for the learnable parameters to be trained. There is also a pretask where the participant finds a number of tokens that correspond to their contribution to the group. This is designated by the variable "token_self". The other variable, "token_opp", is the number of tokens found the opponent's and represents the opoonents contribution to the shared pot that will be later divided by the opponent.

Note that in each trial there is a variable amount of money in the combined earning, so that two equal split_self variables do not represent the same "fairness".

Below is the description of each variable in the dataset, which will be followed by information about the data type of the variable:

trial_type = how much was the contribution [1 = equal, 2 = opponent more, 3 = participant more]
trial_role = the role of the participant [1 = responder, 2 = proposer]
token_opp = number of tokens found by the opponent
token_self = number of tokens found by the participant
combined_earning = amount of money earned in total (note that each token found is £3)
split_opp = the proposed share of the opponent (in £)
split_self = the proposed share for the participant (in £)
splitperc_opp = same but in %
split_perc_self = same but in %
accept = whether the participant responded accept (1) or reject (0)
accepted_amount = if accepted, what is the amount gain (in £)
accepted_perc = same as above but in %
proposed_perc = when participant is the proposer, what is the % proposed to the opponent

For run 44, please develop an innovative computational model for responder decision‐making with the following revised instructions:

1. Compute the normalized offer:  
  N_offer = split_self / combined_earning.

2. Compute the normalized fair share:  
  N_share = token_self / (token_self + token_opp).

3. Define the fairness gap:  
  F = N_offer − N_share.

4. Scale the fairness gap by phi (learnable, bounds [0.5, 1.5]):  
  x = F / phi.

5. For the absolute value |x|, compute the following mandatory components:
  • |x|^(0.5)  
  • ln(1 + 3.4×|x|)  
  • 0.2×atan(1.1×|x|)  
  • 0.1×(1 − exp(−|x|))  
  • 0.05×(1 − exp(−2×|x|))  
  • 0.03×tanh(|x|)  
  • 0.02×sin(0.5×|x|)  
  • 0.012×(1 − cos(0.3×|x|))  
  • 0.005×exp(−|x|)  
  Optionally, include additional terms such as 0.005×sin(2.2×|x|) and 0.002×cos(3.0×|x|).

6. Sum all computed components and add a constant delta = 0.01.

7. Modulate the summed signal by multiplying with the factor [1 + 0.012×sin(|x| + 0.03)].

8. Reorganize the operations by multiplying the power-law term with the logarithmic term to form an Intermediate_Signal, then add the remaining components (atan, exponential, tanh, sine, cosine terms, etc.).

9. Multiply the resulting signal by a fixed constant C drawn from [1.05, 1.10].

10. Apply additional sequential modulation stages:
  a. Multiply with [1 + 0.008×cos(|x| + 0.05)].
  b. Multiply with [1 + 0.005×sin(|x| + 0.10)].
  c. Multiply with [1 + 0.004×cos(|x| + 0.07)].
  d. Multiply with [1 + 0.006×(sin(|x| + 0.02)×cos(|x| + 0.04))].
  e. Optionally, include an extra modulation stage such as [1 + 0.003×(sin(|x| + 0.015)×cos(|x| + 0.035))].

11. Introduce an extra nonlinear blending stage: apply a hyperbolic tangent to the blended signal to compress extreme values before final compression.

12. Add a final tiny offset of 1e-6 for numerical stability.

13. Compress the fully modulated signal by raising it to a fixed exponent E, with E chosen from [0.90, 0.94] (e.g., E ≈ 0.92).

14. Define the final nonlinear transformation as:  
  f(x) = sign(x) × { [ C × (Combined Sums from above, including delta and the power-log blend) × (Product of all modulation factors, including the extra tanh blending) + 1e-6 ]^(E) }.

15. Compute the latent utility:  
  U = beta + gamma × f(F / phi).

16. Derive the acceptance probability:  
  p_accept = 1 / (1 + exp(−U)).

Ensure that exactly three learnable parameters are used:
  • beta (baseline bias) ∈ [–10, 10].  
  • gamma (sensitivity) ∈ [0, 10].  
  • phi (scaling factor) ∈ [0.5, 1.5].

Present your complete mathematical model between <MODEL> and </MODEL> tags, provide detailed JSON-formatted variable descriptions between <VARIABLES> and </VARIABLES> tags, and clearly designate the predicted target variable using <target_variable> tags (set to “accept”).

Encourage creative reordering and blending of the additive and multiplicative operations, innovative phase shifts, and additional nonlinear compressions to fully capture subtle interactions that can improve accuracy, lower BIC, and enhance parameter recovery.

def simulate_model(trial_data, beta=0.0, gamma=1.0, phi=1.0):

        # F = N_offer - N_share
        F = N_offer - N_share

        x = F / phi

        # B = ln(1 + 3.4 * |x|)
        B = math.log(1 + 3.4 * abs(x))
        # C1 = 0.2 * atan(1.1 * |x|)
        C1 = 0.2 * math.atan(1.1 * abs(x))
        # D1 = 0.1 * (1 - exp(-|x|))
        D1 = 0.1 * (1 - math.exp(-abs(x)))

        D2 = 0.05 * (1 - math.exp(-2 * abs(x)))
        # E1 = 0.03 * tanh(|x|)
        E1 = 0.03 * math.tanh(abs(x))
        # F1 = 0.02 * sin(0.5 * |x|)
        F1 = 0.02 * math.sin(0.5 * abs(x))
        # G1 = 0.012 * (1 - cos(0.3 * |x|))

        # H1 = 0.005 * exp(-|x|)
        H1 = 0.005 * math.exp(-abs(x))
        # I1 = 0.005 * sin(2.2 * |x|)
        I1 = 0.005 * math.sin(2.2 * abs(x))
        # J1 = 0.002 * cos(3.0 * |x|)
        J1 = 0.002 * math.cos(3.0 * abs(x))
        delta = 0.01
        # S_base = (A * B) + C1 + D1 + D2 + E1 + F1 + G1 + H1 + I1 + J1 + delta
        S_base = (A * B) + C1 + D1 + D2 + E1 + F1 + G1 + H1 + I1 + J1 + delta
        # M_initial = 1 + 0.012 * sin(|x| + 0.03)
        M_initial = 1 + 0.012 * math.sin(abs(x) + 0.03)
        C_const = 1.075
        # M_seq = (1 + 0.008 * cos(|x| + 0.05)) * (1 + 0.005 * sin(|x| + 0.10)) * (1 + 0.004 * cos(|x| + 0.07)) * (1 + 0.006 * (sin(|x| + 0.02) * cos(|x| + 0.04))) * (1 + 0.003 * (sin(|x| + 0.015) * cos(|x| + 0.035)))
        M_seq = (1 + 0.008 * math.cos(abs(x) + 0.05)) * (1 + 0.005 * math.sin(abs(x) + 0.10)) * (1 + 0.004 * math.cos(abs(x) + 0.07)) * (1 + 0.006 * (math.sin(abs(x) + 0.02) * math.cos(abs(x) + 0.04))) * (1 + 0.003 * (math.sin(abs(x) + 0.015) * math.cos(abs(x) + 0.035)))
        # S_total = C_const * S_base * M_initial * M_seq
        S_total = C_const * S_base * M_initial * M_seq
        # T_mod = tanh(S_total)
        T_mod = math.tanh(S_total)

        E_exp = 0.92

        f_x = (1 if x >= 0 else -1) * (abs(T_mod) + offset)**E_exp
        # U = beta + gamma * f_x
